P.S. I did not intend any attacks (overt or implied) on anyone in the raid. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#6A74B4><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uniemam.showPublicProfile?language=EN>NiemaM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFF00>(4/30/01 3:46:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fsaryrnguildallianceboardfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lessons from Hate</span><hr size=1> I think we worked verry well together as a team in hate this sunday but the reason we were allowed such a luxory of learning the ropes as it were for many was due to the fact that we entered an already broken plane. <br>
<br>
On a traditional hate plane break sticking close is paramount.  We'd have been wiped soo easy if there had been a full pop but of course we were aware we were entering with few pops, no spites up for sure, so it is certainly understandable and good that we could be more relaxed. <br>
<br>
Now its been my exp (from a chanters point of view of course)what a usual hate break can be like. We port up 3 groups strong minimum attempt to make first camp w/o aggroing anything then camp out and come back just in case rinse repeat with rest.  <br>
<br>
